`crates/ctx-scan/tests` is the integration-test suite pinning the observable contracts of `ctx-scan`'s CLI-facing entry points — `summarize`, `check_run`, `update_run`, `prune_run`, and `stop_hook` — against both hermetic in-memory fakes and real tmpdir filesystems. Depending on this crate's public API means these tests are the enforcement mechanism for return shapes, ignore-file seeding, orphan handling, and the no-model-call guarantee of pruning; breaking any of those breaks this suite by design.

All three files share the same fixture pattern: a `FakeFs`/`StubAgent`(or `RecordingAgent`) pair for hermetic logic, plus real-tmpdir tests via `prompts_path()` (resolved from `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`, cwd-independent) and per-test uniquely-named dirs under `std::env::temp_dir()` with manual cleanup. A change to the `Fs`/`Agent` trait signatures in `ctx-summarize` requires updating the fakes in both `reconcile.rs` and `scan.rs` together.

Cross-cutting invariants enforced across files: orphan/reconciliation logic is split by mechanism — hash-diff catches deleted leaf files (dedup'd into `orphan_leaves`), while directory-subtree deletion is invisible to hash-diff and only caught by `find_orphan_artifacts` (tested in `reconcile.rs`, exercised again via `update_run` in `scan.rs`). Pruning and `stop_hook` are both asserted to be strictly non-mutating/no-model where documented (`check_run` read-only, `prune_run`/`update_run` no-agent-call when tree is hash-fresh, `stop_hook` never calls `update_run`). `.context/intent.md`, `.context/README.md`, `.cache`, `.reports` are always spared by pruning at any depth.

`scan.rs` covers the walker/hash/update pipeline and ignore-seeding; `reconcile.rs` covers orphan detection/pruning specifically; `stop_hook.rs` covers the Stop-hook's report-only contract and its `--update`/`--update --approve` escalation logic tied to `MAX_TARGETS`.